#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:28
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. Introduction\n"
"---------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    By editing /etc/inittab, you can achieve all sorts of nifty and\n"
"useful things. This file is the configuration of `init', the utility\n"
"which controls booting, shutting down, etc.; look at the LFS book for\n"
"some details, and also examine the /etc/inittab file given.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:39
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    In this hint, I will show you how to add extra consoles (if, like\n"
"me, you appreciate having 10 or so consoles available), how to have a\n"
"virtual terminal display a log file, and how to run `top' (or any other\n"
"utility you like) on a virtual terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:44
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Note that the virtual terminals used in this hint, /dev/tty1 to\n"
"/dev/tty12, correspond to the screens you get when you press Alt+F1 to\n"
"Alt+F12. If a VT is unused, then it won't pop up when you press its key;\n"
"it will only appear once some data has been sent to it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:48
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"2. Adding extra consoles\n"
"------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    With the /etc/inittab that ships with LFS, you get six consoles (on\n"
"VTs 1 through 6). First, decide which VTs you want to have terminals on.\n"
"Then, add the following line to /etc/inittab for each console that you\n"
"want:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:56
msgid "XXX:2345:respawn:/sbin/agetty ttyXXX 9600"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:58
msgid "(replace XXX with the number of the VT, 7-12)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:62
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    If, like me, you don't want other people to see what was on the\n"
"screen after you finished with your console, you can use some trickery\n"
"to clear the screen after you logout. Firstly, create a script:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:73
msgid ""
"# cat >/sbin/agetty-init.sh <<EOF >#!/bin/sh ># /sbin/agetty-init.sh ># For "
"clearing the screen after you have finished with a console.  > >/sbin/agetty "
"tty$1 9600 >clear >/dev/tty$1 > >EOF # chmod +x /sbin/agetty-init.sh"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:79
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Then, in /etc/inittab, change the console lines. These are in the\n"
"same format as above. The stock LFS file will contain entries starting\n"
"1:, 2:, 3:, 4:, 5: and 6: (not l1: et al.; these are something else).\n"
"Find each such line and delete it. Now add the following line once for\n"
"each console you want:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:81
msgid "cXXX:2345:respawn:/sbin/agetty-init.sh XXX"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:83
msgid "(replace XXX with the number of the VT you want, 1 through 12)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Remember that agetty will print the contents of /etc/issue to the\n"
"screen before its login prompt; you can use this to customise the\n"
"appearance of your login screens. Also, you can put any additional\n"
"actions into `agetty-init.sh' (before or after agetty is called); these\n"
"allow you to customise your system even more.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:93
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3. Log files on a virtual terminal\n"
"----------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:97
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    If you want a VT to display the contents of a log file, you can use\n"
"a simple entry in /etc/inittab. Add a line like the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:99
msgid "log:2345:respawn:/usr/bin/tail -f --retry /var/log/sys.log >/dev/ttyXXX"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:105
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Replace the initial `log:' with any 4-character name you like; as\n"
"long as each identifier is unique, there is no problem. For instance,\n"
"you could use `9x3d:', if it meant something to you. Replace the final\n"
"filename with the name of the log file you want to examine. Finally,\n"
"replace XXX with the number of the VT you want to output to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:109
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"4. Top on a virtual terminal\n"
"----------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    `top' is a great program to have running on a spare VT! It lets you\n"
"see which processes are running, what your CPU is up to, how much memory\n"
"is in use, and so on. To get it running on a spare VT, use the following\n"
"line in /etc/inittab:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:117
msgid "top:2345:respawn:/usr/bin/top d 1 s S c >/dev/ttyXXX </dev/ttyXXX"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Replace XXX with the number of the VT you want to use. Also note the\n"
"parameters we pass to top: `d 1' sets the delay between updates to 1s\n"
"(change this if you want), `s' runs top in secure mode (see the man page\n"
"for details; basically, this stops any old user from killing processes),\n"
"and `S c' are aesthetic options. See `man top' for more info.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    You can use this sort of line to add any program you like on a VT.\n"
"Note that you need to redirect both output and input for an interactive\n"
"program like top to work.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:131
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"5. Caveats\n"
"----------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    If you are trying anything ambitious, please read the information\n"
"in Appendix A, below. This explains the format of /etc/inittab, so you\n"
"are less likely to make a mistake which needs rectifying. Also, before\n"
"you start messing with /etc/inittab, you should probably have some\n"
"backup way of booting into your system (for instance, I use an old SuSE\n"
"6.3 bootable CDROM).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:145
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Although nothing can really go disastrously wrong with this sort of\n"
"setup, sometimes your VTs can get scrambled by programs such as X and\n"
"any sort of graphical login manager. I don't know when this happens, or\n"
"how to avoid or rectify it, but it hasn't caused me any problems. Note\n"
"that I don't use a graphical login, however.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:149
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Jurgen Nagel has reported that his extra consoles don't work\n"
"correctly. He has fixed this by adding an initialisation field to the\n"
"agetty call:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:151
msgid "c2:2345:respawn:/sbin/agetty -I [H[J tty2 9600"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:155
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    The initialisation is <escape>[H<escape>[J and this fixes his\n"
"problem. I can't reproduce this on any of my systems but if you get this\n"
"problem, just add the -I parameter to the agetty call. Thanks Jurgen!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:159
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Appendix A. Format of /etc/inittab explained\n"
"--------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    For the version of init used in LFS, the /etc/inittab file has the\n"
"following format:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:165
msgid "identifier:runlevels:actiontype:command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:169
msgid ""
"`identifier' is a unique identifier, from 1 to 4 characters. Make sure you "
"don't use duplicate identifiers in your file. The identifier has no bearing "
"on how init works; the names don't have to mean anything."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:172
msgid ""
"`runlevels' is a list of the runlevels in which this line should be "
"activated. Read `man init' for more detail about runlevels."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:186
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"`actiontype' is one of the following:\n"
"    respawn         run the command every time it finishes\n"
"    wait            run the command when entering the runlevel, and wait\n"
"                        for it to finish before moving on\n"
"    once            run the command once when entering the runlevel\n"
"    boot            executed only during system bootup (ignores\n"
"                        runlevels)\n"
"    bootwait        as above, only wait for finish\n"
"    off             ignore this entry\n"
"    initdefault     this actually specifies which runlevel is considered\n"
"                        the default on the system (usually 3)\n"
"    sysinit         executed during bootup, before boot/bootwait\n"
"    ctrlaltdel      what to do when the user hits ctrl+alt+del\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:189
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    There are some more actions, but these are more advanced. Details\n"
"are available (see `man inittab' and possibly `man init').\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/inittab.txt:193
msgid ""
"`command' is the commandline to run. Note that the PATH environment variable "
"isn't set: you need to specify the whole path to any executable files."
msgstr ""
